{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491235","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491235"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:38:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:38:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"886"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"886","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/886"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.45,0.36,0.06,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"886"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101932"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"886","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/886"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2019-11-05T09:33:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-05T16:51:28+09:30","updatedAction":"commented","acceptedAt":"2021-09-20T23:20:42+09:30","editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":"2025-09-28 22:10:37"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"886"}},"updatedBy":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"13477"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"9"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84389"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1315"},{"type":"tags","id":"1571"},{"type":"tags","id":"4115"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1170"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3457"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4004"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12940"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17343"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35226"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43045"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44665"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84389"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101932","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101932"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old, G1P1, presents to her general practitioner following a normal pregnancy and delivery. She is three (3) weeks postpartum and currently breast-feeding which she intends to do for at least 12 months. She does not wish to conceive for at least another three years and is tired - she does not want to have to remember to attend for appointments or script refills.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe was taking the combined oral contraceptive pill prior to conception without any issue. She has no significant medical history and her pre-pregnancy cervical screening test was low risk.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following contraceptive options is the most appropriate and can be commenced immediately?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Progesterone only pill","Implanon","Mirena IUD","Lactational amenorrhea","Combined oral contraceptive pill"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has indicated that they want a longer inter-pregnancy interval of three years. Long acting reversible contraception (LARC) in the form of the progestogen implant (\u003Cstrong\u003EImplanon\u003C/strong\u003E), would be a good option for this patient. The implant can be inserted immediately postpartum and safe in breastfeeding mothers. It is also effective for three years but can be removed easily if fertility plans change. The \u003Cstrong\u003ELevonorgestrel intrauterine contraceptive device (Mirena)\u003C/strong\u003E is another LARC option which is safe in breastfeeding however it is associated with increased risk of uterine perforation if inserted between 2-6 weeks postpartum. Current guidelines recommend that the Mirena can be inserted \u0026lt;48hrs post delivery (MEC 2), but is contraindicated from \u0026gt;48hrs to 4 weeks post partum thus would not be an option for this patient today (only 3 weeks post-partum). The Mirena has recently had its duration of action from 5 years to 8 years and would be an option for insertion at a future appointment if this was the patient\u0027s preferred option. Both the Implanon and the Mirena require seven days activity (and therefore condom use) prior to becoming effective for contraception.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eprogesterone only pill\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as the \u0027mini-pill\u0027 is an easily available and commonly prescribed oral medication which can be commenced immediately postpartum and continued throughout the breastfeeding period. It has rapid onset within three days but patients need to adhere to strict daily dosing as there is only a three hour window for efficacy and if this window is missed, barrier contraception is advised for three days. This is not the best option due to short window of efficacy and high requirement for perfect patient compliance. The patient\u0027s preference to not have to continually refill scripts and requiring ongoing contraception for 3 years would make the mini-pill less preferable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELactational amenorrhoea\u003C/strong\u003E often occurs when women are regularly breastfeeding (intervals between feeds of 4-6 hours) however it is not a reliable method of contraception and additional methods including condoms or the Depoprovera injection should be discussed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003ECombined oral contraception pill (COCP)\u003C/strong\u003E or the Nuva-ring can be utilised from six weeks postpartum as breast feeding is often established and the risk of venous thromboembolism is lower than that immediately postpartum. Commencing the COCP or the Nuva-Ring requires following the \u0027seven day rule\u0027 where barrier contraception should be used for the first seven days from commencing or if it has been \u0026gt;48hours since taking the last COCP.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["There is an increased risk of uterine perforation associated with IUCD insertion \u003C6 weeks postpartum."],"references":["Contraception. RANZCOG Patient Handout (January 2020). Available at: https://ranzcog.edu.au/RANZCOG_SITE/media/RANZCOG-MEDIA/Women%27s%20Health/Patient%20information/Contraception.pdf?ext=.pdf. Accessed 26/01/2021","Milroy T, Frayne J. Postnatal care: The general practitioner visit. Australian Journal for General Practitioners. 2022;51:105-10. [internet]. [cited 2023 June 26] Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2022/march/postnatal-care-gp-visit","Mirena (levonorgestrel) intrauterine device, Australian Prescription Medicine Decision Summary, Therapeutic Goods Administration. Available at: https://www.tga.gov.au/resources/auspmd/mirena-levonorgestrel-intrauterine-device"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84389"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"886"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84389","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84389"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-05T16:50:30+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-05T16:50:30+09:30","number":12,"notes":"","plagiarismCheckedAt":null,"plagiarismScore":null,"plagiarismReportUrl":null},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"886"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101932"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"13477"}},"generation":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/